\f2\i \cf0 What you pass:
\f1\i0  North from Trevi along 
\f0\b Via dei Condotti
\f1\b0  \'97 Rome's most famous luxury shopping street, running in a straight line directly to Piazza di Spagna. The street itself is historically interesting: the corridor between the old aristocratic quarter and the foreign-resident quarter, a commercial spine unchanged since the 18th century. Piazza di Spagna opens at the far end with the steps rising straight ahead and the Barcaccia fountain at the base.\uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Narrative thread:
\f1\i0  Via dei Condotti as a social boundary line \'97 the Rome of ancient ruins gives way here to the Rome of Grand Tour foreigners, expatriate artists, and Romantic poets. The fountain at the bottom of the steps was designed as a sinking boat because the water pressure from the aqueduct was too low to power a conventional fountain. That constraint produced one of Rome's most distinctive objects.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
