\fs24 \cf0 W19 \'97 Fontana di Trevi (4 min script)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Anchor: coin-throwing ritual\uc0\u8232 Pivot: invented entirely by the 1954 film "Three Coins in the Fountain" \'97 before that, no established coin-throwing tradition existed here\uc0\u8232 Register: sociological \'97 how invented rituals become real faster than ancient ones\uc0\u8232 Key facts to research: the Acqua Vergine aqueduct (19 BC, still the water source), the 17th-century Baroque facade (Nicola Salvi, 1762 completion), the \'801.5M/year donated to charity (Caritas) from the coins, the specific "invented in 1954" claim (verify against older sources mentioning coins at Trevi)\uc0\u8232 Physical direction: the fountain appears suddenly at the end of a narrow street \'97 open with that reveal. Then turn the listener around to look at the palazzo behind them (the Palazzo Poli whose facade the fountain is built against).\uc0\u8232 Forward hook: an aqueduct that has been flowing for 2,000 years is about to take you somewhere\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 W20 \'97 Spanish Steps / Scalinata di Trinit\'e0 dei Monti (4 min script)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Anchor: the famous staircase \'97 "Spanish Steps"\uc0\u8232 Pivot 1 \'97 the name: the steps are called Spanish because of the Spanish Embassy at the base, but they were commissioned and paid for by a French diplomat (\'c9tienne Gueffier), designed by Italian architect Francesco de Sanctis, and completed in 1725. Almost everything about the name is wrong.\uc0\u8232 Pivot 2 \'97 the fountain: the Barcaccia ("the old boat") at the base was designed by Pietro Bernini \'97 Gian Lorenzo's father \'97 in 1627. It's designed as a sinking boat specifically because the Acqua Vergine aqueduct didn't have enough pressure at this point to power a conventional upward-spray fountain. The engineering constraint became the aesthetic.\uc0\u8232 Pivot 3 \'97 the pink house on the right: the Keats-Shelley Memorial House, where John Keats died in February 1821, aged 25. He had come to Rome because his doctors believed the climate might help his tuberculosis. He knew it wouldn't. He wrote in a letter from this room that he felt he was "leading a posthumous existence." He died looking out at the steps. Shelley drowned the following year off the coast of Livorno. Both are buried in the Protestant Cemetery near Pyramid, which you may pass on the way to the Appian Way.\uc0\u8232 Physical direction: Look left at the pink house immediately as you arrive (Keats-Shelley house, ground floor). Look up at Trinit\'e0 dei Monti at the summit. Look down at the Barcaccia. Then: how many steps? 135.\uc0\u8232 Key facts to verify: exact nationality of the funder (French diplomat Gueffier \'97 confirm), Pietro Bernini's authorship of Barcaccia (confirm vs Gian Lorenzo), Keats's exact age at death (25 \'97 confirm), the "posthumous existence" letter (confirm exact quote and source)\uc0\u8232 Forward hook: the aqueduct that filled this fountain and the Trevi has been running since 19 BC \'97 it's taking you west now, toward the river\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

